<paragraph blockId="8.[707,1194,194,693]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[731,845,513,534]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a patronym honoring Mr. Edward G. Riley, entomology collection manager at 
<collectingRegion box="[907,964,566,587]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="8" pageNumber="529">Texas</collectingRegion>
A&amp;M University and specialist on the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[875,1023,593,614]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chrysomelidae</taxonomicName>
. He was the first to notice the distinctiveness of the unusual specimen, designated herein as 
<typeStatus box="[994,1087,646,667]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529">holotype</typeStatus>
, from the TAMU collection.
</paragraph>
